<font color="#FF0000">REAL CHANGE OR NOT?</font><br>
<tt>Fri Jul 18 17:43:49 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I too am baffled by the reaction of many Vietnamese and the government in their response to now &quot;open&quot; relations with the U.S. Government.  I am amazed that Vietnam has been so open to this renewal of relations with a country that only recently decided that a trade embargo was unnecessary.  Why was it necessary in the first place?  It seems like a strange way to react to having thousands of people killed on both sides.  I liked what Joe DeLeva said about this renewal of relations perhaps being a way of understanding the past. Perhaps I'm a little cynical, but  I have been in the U.S. since 1975 and I don't believe that many people have learned from the war.  The U.S. went through a phase where Vietnam War movies were popular to make and popular to watch and talk about, but did it really change peoples' perceptions about what is right and wrong?  I'm not trying to anger the masses, but I'm curious to know what you think.<br><br>
I think it's strange that many Vets that I have met insist on telling me all the places they were in Vietnam as soon as they find out I'm Vietnamese.  Why would I want to know all the places that you were at killing Vietnamese?  Has there been a revolution in the way that people are thinking about the U.S. involvement in the war?  I have no idea, but I would really appreciate some honest feedback.<br><br>
I've never shared these thoughts, and I'm afraid that they've come off as very negative.  But I'm just confused.  I am not personally angry at anyone because of their involvement in the war, but more in the system that believes that it is so right and justified in all that it does that it is okay to kill people.  I don't believe the government cared about the people on either sides, only about their twisted ideology.  <br><br>
-Diem Do
